Has that been a cost-efficient kind of thing, that effort?
On the overall picture, absolutely.
Yes, sir.
It might be...
It might have been more economical to put a bulldozer over here and cut down all the trees and start building houses.
However, by the time you start planting the trees back and reforest the land back, it's going to cost you more.
So the way it has been done for a long time, and on the overall cost effectiveness, it is the best way we're doing it.
Because you can never, never be able to duplicate the natural environment, no matter how hard you try.
And I understand that that design has also contributed to making your utility systems, your fluids, your water supply systems, drainage, and all that much more cost efficient.
Is that right?
Or not?
Well, that's a reasonable thought.
It can go both ways.
However, the increment, if there is an increment of cost there, it's so minute you're not going to be able to find it.
Yes, there is.
It's obvious.
I'm not going to sit down over here and argue the point at all.
If you had a grid system, for example, a grid system of streets, and then the reason to assume

And therefore, every time you get away from the cord,
system, and then you've got to put another manhole.

You pay over a 30-year period, so you don't even see it, really.
It's not even the quote of the purchase and the price, because you pay over a 30-year period of time.
So that's your only disadvantage, if any, I would call it that.

Do you anticipate the great expansion that has been projected as changing the character, possibly, of the woodlands, or creating greater difficulties in carrying out this basic theme of preservation of the environment?
No.

The people who live here in the wilderness, the people who will carry the ball after us, I believe they will see it fit to maintain, because they're not going to be able to recreate the natural environment that we have been able to maintain.
There's going to be some scouring, and there's going to be some scars left.
But you would be surprised how quickly this land heals itself.

taking rides around here at night.

Damage it.
